=== Booleans

Booleans in Morloc are represented as `True` or `False` under the `Bool`
type. Comparison and logical operators can be imported from the `root` modules.

==== Literals and basic use

[source, morloc]
----
yes :: Bool
yes = True

no :: Bool
no = False
----

==== Comparison operators

The `Eq` and `Ord` typeclasses in `root` provide the standard comparison
operators. They work over any type with the appropriate instance --
integers, reals, strings, and tuples and lists of comparable values.

[cols="1,2", options="header"]
|===
| Operator | Meaning

| `==`  | equal
| `!=`  | not equal
| `<`   | less than
| `<=`  | less than or equal
| `>`   | greater than
| `>=`  | greater than or equal
|===

[source, morloc]
----
import root-py

isPositive :: Int -> Bool
isPositive x = x > 0

sameLength :: [a] -> [b] -> Bool
sameLength xs ys = length xs == length ys
----

==== Logical operators

The `root` module defines logical conjunction (`&&`), disjunction (`||`),
negation (`not`), exclusive-or (`xor`), and not-and (`nand`):

[cols="1,2", options="header"]
|===
| Operator | Meaning

| `&&`   | logical AND
| `\|\|` | logical OR
| `not`  | logical negation (prefix function)
| `xor`  | exclusive OR
| `nand` | NOT AND
|===

`&&` and `||` are short-circuiting and right-associative. `&&` binds tighter
than `||`, matching the convention of most languages:

[source, morloc]
----
inRange :: Int -> Int -> Int -> Bool
inRange lo hi x = lo <= x && x <= hi

isWeekend :: Int -> Bool
isWeekend day = day == 0 || day == 6

isWeekday :: Int -> Bool
isWeekday day = not (isWeekend day)
----

==== Boolean-valued list functions

The `root` module provides several functions in the `Foldable` family that
return `Bool`:

[cols="1,2", options="header"]
|===
| Function | Signature

| `any`  | `Foldable f => (a -> Bool) -> f a -> Bool`
| `all`  | `Foldable f => (a -> Bool) -> f a -> Bool`
| `elem` | `(Foldable f, Eq a) => a -> f a -> Bool`
|===

`any` returns `True` if the predicate holds for at least one element.  `all`
returns `True` only if the predicate holds for every element.  `elem` checks
membership using `==`.

[source, morloc]
----
hasNegative :: [Int] -> Bool
hasNegative = any (< 0)

allPositive :: [Int] -> Bool
allPositive = all (> 0)

containsZero :: [Int] -> Bool
containsZero = elem 0
----

==== Guards

Booleans drive Morloc's guard syntax. A guard alternative starts with `?` and
selects the first branch whose condition evaluates to `True`; the `:` line is
the fallthrough:

[source, morloc]
----
classify :: Int -> Str
classify x
  ? x < 0     = "negative"
  ? x == 0    = "zero"
  : "positive"
----

See the Guards section for a full description of guard syntax.

